# Backend2 API

FastAPI backend for OCR-based extraction and trend analytics for:

- Lipid profile: total cholesterol, LDL, HDL, triglycerides
- Blood pressure (systolic/diastolic)
- Heart rate
- Oxygen saturation (SpO2)

The service supports report OCR ingestion and manual metric entry for patient trend graphs.

## Stack

- FastAPI
- Tesseract OCR (via pytesseract)
- PostgreSQL (SQLAlchemy + Alembic)

## 1) Setup

1. Install Python 3.11+
2. Install Tesseract OCR and ensure it is in PATH (or set `TESSERACT_CMD`)
3. Create database in PostgreSQL: `lab_analytics`
4. Copy `.env.example` to `.env` and update values

## 2) Install

```bash
pip install -e .
```

## 3) Migrate DB

```bash
alembic upgrade head
```

## 4) Run

```bash
uvicorn app.main:app --reload --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8010
```

## API

- `POST /api/v1/patients/{patient_id}/reports/upload`
  - multipart form-data: file + optional `reported_at` (ISO datetime)
  - runs OCR + parsing + stores report and measurements
- `POST /api/v1/patients/{patient_id}/reports/ingest-drive`
  - optional query: `folder_path`, `reported_at`
  - scans a drive folder for supported report files (`.pdf`, `.png`, `.jpg`, `.jpeg`, `.tif`, `.tiff`, `.bmp`, `.webp`)
  - runs OCR + parsing for each file and stores report metadata + extracted measurements in PostgreSQL
- `POST /api/v1/patients/{patient_id}/reports/auto-ingest`
  - json body: `documents` array with metadata (objectName, fileName, mimeType, issuedAt, uploadedAt)
  - downloads documents from minio, runs OCR + parsing, stores measurements in PostgreSQL
  - called by frontend when patient loads health analysis to auto-populate trend graphs
- `GET /api/v1/patients/{patient_id}/trends`
  - optional query: `metric`, `from_date`, `to_date`
- `POST /api/v1/patients/{patient_id}/measurements/manual`
  - json body: `metric_code`, `value`, optional `measured_at`, optional `unit`
- `POST /api/v1/patient/ai-health-checker/suggestions`
  - json body: `symptoms` + optional `conversation` array (`role`, `text`)
  - returns follow-up question flow and final specialist recommendation
- `GET /api/v1/patient/ai-health-checker/status`
  - checks local Ollama model availability and active inference source

## AI doctor suggestion setup

This module reuses the prompt from `../ai/SYSTEM_PROMPT.txt` and runs on local Ollama by default. You can also switch it to Groq's OpenAI-compatible API if you want hosted inference without a local GPU.

Optional environment variables:

- `AI_CONVERSATION_PROVIDER` (default: `ollama`, set to `groq` to use Groq)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_OLLAMA_URL` (default: `http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/chat`)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_OLLAMA_MODEL` (default: `llama3:8b`)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_GROQ_API_KEY` (required when `AI_CONVERSATION_PROVIDER=groq`)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_GROQ_MODEL` (default: `llama-3.3-70b-versatile`)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_GROQ_BASE_URL` (default: `https://api.groq.com/openai/v1`)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_SYSTEM_PROMPT_PATH` (default: `../ai/SYSTEM_PROMPT.txt`)
- `AI_CONVERSATION_TIMEOUT_SECONDS` (default: `25.0`)

Groq is called through the same chat-completions message format as OpenAI-compatible APIs, so the triage prompt and JSON response contract stay unchanged.

## Triage LLM setup

The triage endpoint uses `LLM_PROVIDER` and OpenAI-compatible settings:

- `LLM_PROVIDER` (default: `openai`; supported: `openai`, `anthropic`, `gemini`)
- `OPENAI_API_KEY`
- `OPENAI_BASE_URL` (default: `https://api.openai.com/v1`)
- `OPENAI_MODEL` (default: `gpt-4o-mini`)

If you use a Groq key (`gsk_...`) in `OPENAI_API_KEY`, the backend now auto-routes to Groq's OpenAI-compatible URL and a compatible default model.

The trend endpoint always reads from the persisted `measurements` table, so OCR-extracted data remains available for permanent graphing.

Swagger docs: `http://localhost:8010/docs`
